1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,209
The person determined to achieve maximum success learns the principle that progress is made one step at a time.

2
00:00:08,480 --> 00:00:10,930
A house is built a brick at a time.

3
00:00:11,199 --> 00:00:14,050
Football games are won a play at a time.

4
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:18,290
A department store grows bigger one new customer at a time.

5
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:22,690
Every big accomplishment is a series of little accomplishments.

6
00:00:23,280 --> 00:00:29,249
Eric Severide, the well-known author and correspondent, reported in Reader's Digest,

7
00:00:29,280 --> 00:00:36,610
April 1957, that the best advice he ever received was the principle of the next mile.

8
00:00:36,879 --> 00:00:38,850
Here's part of what he said.

9
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:49,969
During World War II, I and several others had to parachute from a crippled Army transport plane into the mountainous jungle on the Burma-India border.

10
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:56,209
It was several weeks before an armed relief expedition could reach us, and then we began a painful,

11
00:00:56,209 --> 00:00:59,410
plodding march out to civilized India.

12
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:06,690
We were faced by a 140-mile trek over mountains in August heat and monsoon rains.

13
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:12,769
In the first hour of the march, I rammed a boot nail deep into one foot.

14
00:01:12,959 --> 00:01:18,530
By evening, I had bleeding blisters the size of a 50 cent piece on both feet.

15
00:01:18,719 --> 00:01:21,650
Could I hobble 140 miles?

16
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:25,969
Could the others, some in worse shape than I, complete such a distance?

17
00:01:26,480 --> 00:01:28,449
We were convinced we could not.

18
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:31,170
But we could hobble to that ridge.

19
00:01:31,360 --> 00:01:34,690
We could make the next friendly village for the night.

20
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:37,729
And that, of course, was all we had to do.

21
00:01:38,480 --> 00:01:44,449
When I relinquished my job and income to undertake a book of a quarter of a million words,

22
00:01:44,719 --> 00:01:49,090
I could not bear to let my mind dwell on the whole scope of the project.

23
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:54,930
I would surely have abandoned what has become my deepest source of professional pride.

24
00:01:55,360 --> 00:02:01,810
I tried to think only of the next paragraph, not the next page and certainly not the next chapter.

25
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:08,530
Thus, for six solid months, I never did anything but set down one paragraph after another.

26
00:02:08,719 --> 00:02:11,250
The book wrote itself.
